1. The Setup (Before you build)
Open UiPath Studio.
Create a Project: Click on Process (under "New Project").
Name it: Give it a name like Practical_Automation and click Create.
Open the Workspace: Click on Open Main Workflow in the center of the screen. You now have a blank canvas.

2. Implementing the Controls (Step-by-Step)
a. Attach Window (The Container)
This is the "Parent" activity. You put other actions inside it.
Search for Attach Window in the Activities panel (Left side).
Drag it into the Sequence in the middle.
Click "Indicate window on screen".
Click the window you want to automate (e.g., a Chrome page or a Folder).

Inside the 'Do' block: Now drag any other activity (like Type Into) inside this box.

b. Anchor Base (Finding by Label)
Use this when a text box doesn't have a unique ID.
Drag the Anchor Base activity into your workflow.
Left Side (Anchor): Drag a Find Element activity here. Click "Indicate" and select the label text (e.g., the word "Username").
Right Side (Action): Drag a Type Into activity here. Click "Indicate" and select the empty box next to that label.

In Properties, ensure AnchorPosition is set to Auto or Left.

c. Element Exists (The "Safety Check")
Use this to see if a button is there before clicking it.

Drag Element Exists into the sequence.
Click "Indicate on screen" and select a button or logo.
Variable Creation: In the Properties panel, look for Exists. Click the empty box next to it and press Ctrl + K. Type isFound.
The Logic: Drag an If activity below it.
In the Condition, type isFound.

In the Then block, drag a Click activity. (The bot will only click if the element was found).

d. Find Children (Gathering a List)
Drag Find Children into the sequence.
Click "Indicate on screen" and select a container (like a Taskbar or a Dropdown menu).
Variable Creation: In the Properties (under Output > Children), press Ctrl + K and type childElements.
Looping: Drag a For Each activity. Set the input to childElements.
Inside the loop, use a Log Message to print item.Selector.ToString.

3. How to Run & Test
Save: Always click the Save icon (Disk icon) at the top left.
Debug/Run: * Press F5 to run the whole thing.
Press the Debug File button to watch it run step-by-step.
Watch the Output: Keep an eye on the Output Panel (usually at the bottom left). It will tell you if the bot succeeded or if it crashed and why.

4. Troubleshooting for Beginners
"Activity not found": If you can't find an activity, click the Filter icon in the Activities panel and check "Show Classic".

The Blue Warning Icon: If you see a small blue "!" on your activity, it means a property is missing (usually you forgot to create a variable or indicate an element).

Selectors: If the bot fails to find an element, click the Hamburger menu (≡) on the activity and select Edit Selector to see what the bot is looking for.
